<section xml:id="PR6" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Properties and Graphs of Rational Functions (PR6) </title>
  <objectives>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <xi:include href="outcomes/06.ptx" />
      </li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>
  <subsection>
    <title>Activities</title>

    <definition xml:id="def-rational-func">
      <statement>
        <p> A function <m>r</m> is <term>rational</term><idx>rational function</idx> provided that it is possible to write <m>r</m> as the ratio of two polynomials, <m>p</m> and <m>q</m>. That is, <m>r</m> is rational provided that for some polynomial functions <m>p</m> and <m>q</m>, we have <me>
          r(x) = \frac{p(x)}{q(x)}\text{.}</me>
        
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <activity xml:id="activity-rf-domain-and-zeros">
      <introduction>
        <p>Consider the rational function <me>
          r(x) = \frac{x^2-4x-5}{x^2+x-6}\text{.}</me> </p>
        
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <p>Find <m>r(1) </m>, <m>r(2) </m>, and <m>r(3)</m>.  </p>
      </task>
      <task>
        <p>One answer above gave us some information about the domain of <m>r(x)</m>. Which one? Why?</p>
      </task>
      <task>
        <p>Another answer gave us some information about the zeros of <m>r(x)</m>. Which one? Why?</p>
      </task>
      <task>
        <p>Another answer gave us some information about a point on the graph of <m>r(x)</m> that is not a zero. Which one? Why?</p>
      </task>
    </activity>

    <definition xml:id="def-rf-domain">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>p</m> and <m>q</m> be polynomial functions so that <m>r(x) = \frac{p(x)}{q(x)}</m> is a rational function.  The <term>domain</term><idx>domain of a rational function</idx> of <m>r</m> is the set of all real numbers except those for which <m>q(x) = 0</m>.
        </p>
       
      </statement>
    </definition>
   
  
    <activity xml:id="activity-rf-matching">
      <introduction>
        <p>Consider the following six graphs of rational functions:</p>
        <sbsgroup>
          <sidebyside width="30%">
            <image>
              <sageplot>
                f(x) = 2*x/(x^2-2*x-8)
                p=plot(f, (x, -7, 7), ymin=-7, ymax=7, color='blue', thickness=3, detect_poles=True)
                p+=parametric_plot((-2,x),(x,-8,8),color='red',linestyle="--")
                p+=parametric_plot((4,x),(x,-8,8),color='red',linestyle="--")
                p+=parametric_plot((x,0),(x,-7,7),color='red',linestyle="--")
                p+=text('Graph A', (0, 8), fontsize=18, color='black')
                p
              </sageplot>
            </image>
            <image>
              <sageplot>
                f(x) = (x^2+3)/(2*x^2-8)-1
                p=plot(f, (x, -7, 7), ymin=-7, ymax=7, color='blue', thickness=3, detect_poles=True)
                p+=parametric_plot((-2,x),(x,-8,8),color='red',linestyle="--")
                p+=parametric_plot((2,x),(x,-8,8),color='red',linestyle="--")
                p+=parametric_plot((x,-1),(x,-7,7),color='red',linestyle="--")
                p+=text('Graph B', (0, 8), fontsize=18, color='black')
                p
              </sageplot>
            </image>
            <image>
              <sageplot>
                f(x) = 1-(x^2+3)/(2*x^2-8)
                p=plot(f, (x, -7, 7), ymin=-7, ymax=7, color='blue', thickness=3, detect_poles=True)
                p+=parametric_plot((-2,x),(x,-8,8),color='red',linestyle="--")
                p+=parametric_plot((2,x),(x,-8,8),color='red',linestyle="--")
                p+=parametric_plot((x,1),(x,-7,7),color='red',linestyle="--")
                p+=text('Graph C', (0, 8), fontsize=18, color='black')
                p
              </sageplot>
            </image>
          </sidebyside>
          <sidebyside width="30%">
            <image>
              <sageplot>
                f(x) = 2*x/(x^2-2*x-8)-3
                p=plot(f, (x, -7, 7), ymin=-7, ymax=7, color='blue', thickness=3, detect_poles=True)
                p+=parametric_plot((-2,x),(x,-8,8),color='red',linestyle="--")
                p+=parametric_plot((4,x),(x,-8,8),color='red',linestyle="--")
                p+=parametric_plot((x,-3),(x,-7,7),color='red',linestyle="--")
                p+=text('Graph D', (0, 8), fontsize=18, color='black')
                p
              </sageplot>
            </image>
            <image>
              <sageplot>
                f(x) = (x^2+3)/(2*x^2-8)
                p=plot(f, (x, -7, 7), ymin=-7, ymax=7, color='blue', thickness=3, detect_poles=True)
                p+=parametric_plot((-2,x),(x,-8,8),color='red',linestyle="--")
                p+=parametric_plot((2,x),(x,-8,8),color='red',linestyle="--")
                p+=parametric_plot((x,0),(x,-7,7),color='red',linestyle="--")
                p+=text('Graph E', (0, 8), fontsize=18, color='black')
                p
              </sageplot>
            </image>
            <image>
              <sageplot>
                f(x) = -2*x/(x^2-2*x-8)
                p=plot(f, (x, -7, 7), ymin=-7, ymax=7, color='blue', thickness=3, detect_poles=True)
                p+=parametric_plot((-2,x),(x,-8,8),color='red',linestyle="--")
                p+=parametric_plot((4,x),(x,-8,8),color='red',linestyle="--")
                p+=parametric_plot((x,0),(x,-7,7),color='red',linestyle="--")
                p+=text('Graph F', (0, 8), fontsize=18, color='black')
                p
              </sageplot>
            </image>
          </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <p>Which of the graphs above represents the function <m>f(x)=\frac{2x}{x^2-2x-8}</m>?</p>
      </task>
      <task>
        <p>Which of the graphs above represents the function <m>g(x)=\frac{x^2+3}{2x^2-8}</m>?</p>
      </task>
    </activity>
    
  </subsection>

